Here's a modern MSTest approach using `Microsoft.Extensions.Http` testing patterns:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class DataFetcherTests
{
    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_ReturnsContent_OnSuccess()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("hello", HttpStatusCode.OK);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com");

        Assert.AreEqual("hello", result);
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_Throws_OnNonSuccessStatus()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("", HttpStatusCode.NotFound);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<HttpRequestException>(
            () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com"));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public async Task FetchAsync_HonoursCancellationToken()
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        cts.Cancel();

        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("data", HttpStatusCode.OK);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        await Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<TaskCanceledException>(
            () => fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", cts.Token));
    }

    [TestMethod]
    [Timeout(5000)] // fails test if it hangs beyond 5s
    public async Task FetchAsync_CompletesWithinTimeout()
    {
        var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("fast", HttpStatusCode.OK);
        using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
        var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

        var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com");

        Assert.AreEqual("fast", result);
    }

    private sealed class MockHttpMessageHandler(
        string content, HttpStatusCode statusCode) : HttpMessageHandler
    {
        protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
            HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
        {
            cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            var response = new HttpResponseMessage(statusCode)
            {
                Content = new StringContent(content)
            };
            return Task.FromResult(response);
        }
    }
}
```

**Key modern MSTest patterns used:**

| Pattern | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| `async Task` test methods | MSTest natively awaits them — no `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` needed |
| `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync` | MSTest v3+ preferred over `ThrowsExceptionAsync` (exact type match) |
| `[Timeout(ms)]` | Fails hung tests; works with async methods in MSTest v3+ |
| `CancellationToken` forwarding | Verified via a pre-cancelled token + `ThrowIfCancellationRequested` in the handler |
| Custom `HttpMessageHandler` | Avoids mocking frameworks; gives full control over `SendAsync` |

**MSTest v3+/v4 note:** If using `MSTest.Sdk` with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `[Timeout]` uses `CancellationToken` injection via `TestContext`. You can also accept it directly:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Timeout(3000)]
public async Task FetchAsync_WithInjectedTimeout(CancellationToken timeoutToken)
{
    // timeoutToken is automatically cancelled when [Timeout] expires
    var handler = new MockHttpMessageHandler("data", HttpStatusCode.OK);
    using var client = new HttpClient(handler);
    var fetcher = new DataFetcher(client);

    var result = await fetcher.FetchAsync("https://example.com", timeoutToken);

    Assert.AreEqual("data", result);
}
```

This `CancellationToken` parameter injection is an MSTest v3.4+ feature that lets the test timeout naturally cancel your async call rather than aborting the thread.
